<sect1 id="kapp-features">
<title>&mathematik; features</title>
<itemizedlist>
  <listitem><para>Nice Worksheet view for evaulating Expressions</para></listitem>
  <listitem><para>View of plotting results inside the worksheet</para></listitem>
  <listitem><para>Easy plugin based structure to add different Backends</para></listitem>
  <listitem><para>GetHotNewStuff integration to up/download example worksheets</para></listitem>
  <listitem><para>Typesetting of mathematical formulas using LaTeX</para></listitem>
  <listitem><para>Backend aware Syntax highlighting</para></listitem>
  <listitem><para>Plugin based assistant dialogs for common tasks (like integrating a function or entering a matrix)</para></listitem>
</itemizedlist>
</sect1>

<sect1 id="backends">
<title>The &mathematik; backends</title>
<para>
  &mathematik; offers you several choices for the backend, you want to use it with.
  Your choice should depend on what task you want to achive. 
</para>
<para>
  Currently the following backends are available:
  <variablelist>
    <varlistentry>
      <term>Sage:</term>
      <listitem>
	<para>
	  Sage is a free open-source mathematics software system licensed under the GPL.
	  It combines the power of many existing open-source packages into a common Python-based interface.
	  See <link>http://sagemath.org</link> for more information.
	</para>
	</listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
      <term>Maxima:</term>
      <listitem>
	<para>
	  Maxima is a system for the manipulation of symbolic and numerical expressions,
	  including differentiation, integration, Taylor series, Laplace transforms, 
	  ordinary differential equations, systems of linear equations, polynomials, and sets,
	  lists, vectors, matrices, and tensors. Maxima yields high precision numeric results
	  by using exact fractions, arbitrary precision integers, and variable precision 
	  floating point numbers. Maxima can plot functions and data in two and three dimensions.
	  See <link>http://maxima.sourceforge.net</link> for more information.
	</para>
      </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
      <term>R:</term>
      <listitem>
	<para>
	  R is a language and environment for statistical computing and graphics, similar to the S language and environment.
	  It provides a wide variety of statistical (linear and nonlinear modelling,
	  classical statistical tests, time-series analysis, classification, clustering, ...)
	  and graphical techniques, and is highly extensible. The S language is often the 
	  vehicle of choice for research in statistical methodology, 
	  and R provides an Open Source route to participation in that activity.
	  See <link>http://www.r-project.org</link> for more information.
	</para>
      </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
  </variablelist>
</para>
</sect1>

<sect1>
<title>The &mathematik; Workspace</title>
<para>
<screenshot>
  <screeninfo>Screenshot of the &mathematik; Workspace</screeninfo>
  <mediaobject>
    <imageobject>
      <imagedata fileref="screenshot.png" format="PNG"/>
    </imageobject>
    <imageobject>
      <imagedata fileref="screenshot.eps" format="EPS"/>
    </imageobject>
    <textobject>
      <phrase>Screenshot of the &mathematik; Workspace</phrase>
    </textobject>
  </mediaobject>
</screenshot>
</para>
<para>
  The Worksheet interface of &mathematik; consists of three parts:
  <orderedlist>
    <listitem><para>The Tab-Bar where you can switch through your opened worksheets</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>A help panel, where help for a specific command is displayed if you write ?command</para></listitem>
    <listitem><para>The Worksheet</para></listitem>
  </orderedlist>
</para>
<sect2>
<title>The Worksheet</title>
<para>
  The worksheet is the basic area for working with &mathematik;. In it you can enter
  Expressions, let the backend calculate, and look at the results.
  The commands, the worksheets accept are depending on the chosen backend, so you should
  the appropriate Documentation (the Show Help button takes you there directly).
  If you know the command, but you need additional information, you can type "?command",
  and contextual help will appear on the right of the worksheet.
  If you want to see example worksheets, you can go to <guimenuitem>Download Example Worksheets</guimenuitem>
  in the file-menu, and download worksheets other users have published.
</para>
<sect3>
  <title>Settings</title>
  <para>
    The <guimenu>Settings</guimenu> menu allows you to change some settings of the appearance of your
    current worksheet.
  </para>
  <variablelist>
    <varlistentry>
      <term>Typesetting using LaTeX</term>
      <listitem>
	<para>
	  This setting changes the way, results are presented to you. If enabled, it passes thre result through
	  the LaTex system, to produce vissually appealing formulas. For Example <quote>3*x^2*sqrt(2)*x+2/3</quote> becomes 
	  <inlinemediaobject>
	      <imageobject>
		<imagedata fileref="latex_formula.png" format="PNG"/>
	      </imageobject>
	      <imageobject>
		<imagedata fileref="latex_formula.eps" format="EPS"/>
	      </imageobject>
	      <textobject>3*x^2*sqrt(2)*x+2/3</textobject>
	  </inlinemediaobject>
	</para>
      </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
      <term>Syntax Highlighting</term>
      <listitem>
	<para>
	  Syntax Highlighting increases the readability of code, by highlighting
	  Keywords or matching brackets in different colors
	</para>
      </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
      <term>Tab Completion</term>
      <listitem>
	<para>
	  When this is enabled, &mathematik; will show you possible completions
	  for the command you are currently typing when you press the Tab-key. If there is only one choice
	  left, it will insert the rest of the command for you.
	</para>
      </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
  </variablelist>
  <varlistentry>
    <term>Line Numbers</term>
    <listitem>
      <para>
	This setting controls, wether the different Expressions should have a number in front, so you can,
	for example in Maxima recall older results with the <quote>%O1</quote> command
      </para>
    </listitem>
  </varlistentry>
</sect3>
</sect2>
</sect1>

